Laurel/DeRose and Laurel/Honda General Plan Amendments Traffic Analysis
This report presents the results of the General Plan Amendment traffic impact analysis conducted for the
Laurel-DeRose and Laurel-Honda sites in Morgan Hill, California. The Laurel-DeRose site consists of a
6.81-acre vacant lot located west of the 4.64-acre vacant Laurel-Honda site. The City of Morgan Hill file
number for the Laurel-DeRose GPA site is GPA-13-02 and for the Laurel-Honda GPA site is GPA-14-01.
The proposed amendments consist of the change of the currently adopted General Plan land use for
each of the sites to proposed new land uses. Currently, there are no specific development plans for the
project sites. However, for the purposes of this study, maximum development scenarios on the project
sites were evaluated, based on information provided by City staff. The proposed land use amendments
At the Laurel-DeRose site, the currently adopted General Plan land use designation and zoning for the
site is Multi-Family Low on 4.54 acres and Commercial on 2.27 acres. The proposed amendment includes
the conversion of the Commercial portion of the site to Multi-Family Low to include up to 95 dwelling units
At the Laurel-Honda site, the currently adopted General Plan land use designation and zoning for the site
is Multi-Family Low on 2.32 acres and Commercial on 2.32 acres. The proposed amendment includes the
conversion of the Multi-Family Low portion of the site to Commercial that can include approximately 8,400
s.f. of commercial space and up to 90 hotel rooms on the entire project site.
The purpose of the study is to identify the potential traffic impacts related to the proposed land use
amendment. The potential impacts related to the proposed amendment were evaluated following the
standards and methodologies set forth by the City of Morgan Hill and the Santa Clara Valley
Transportation Authority (VTA). The VTA administers the County Congestion Management Program
The study includes an analysis of AM and PM peak-hour traffic conditions for eleven signalized
intersections, five unsignalized intersections, and eight directional freeway segments. The study
intersections were selected based upon the estimated number of project trips through the intersection (10
or more trips per lane per hour).
Traffic conditions at all of the study intersections were analyzed for the weekday AM and PM peak hours.
The weekday AM peak hour of traffic is generally between 7:00 and 9:00 AM and the weekday PM peak
hour is typically between 4:00 and 6:00 PM. It is during these periods that the most congested traffic
conditions occur on a typical weekday.

This section presents the methods used to determine the traffic conditions for each scenario described

The data required for the analysis were obtained from previous traffic studies, new traffic counts, the City

Laurel/DeRose and Laurel/Honda General Plan Amendments Traffic Analysis
The City of Morgan Hill travel demand forecasting (TDF) model was developed to help the City project
peak hour traffic impacts attributable to changes proposed to the City’s General Plan. The model is
implemented using the TransCAD transportation planning software. The City of Morgan Hill model
includes the three elements traditionally associated with models of this kind. These elements include:
The fundamental structure of the model includes a representation of the City’s street system (highway
network) that defines street segments (links) identified by end points (nodes). Each roadway link is further
represented by key characteristics (link attributes) that describe the length, travel speeds, and vehicular
capacity of the roadway segment. Small geographic areas (traffic analysis zones also called TAZ’s) are
used to quantify the existing and planned land use activity throughout the City’s planning area.
The data in the model includes information about the number of households (single family, multi family
and senior housing) and employment based variables (retail, office, manufacturing, medical, industrial,
etc.) expressed in square feet of gross building area. In addition, the land use database includes student
enrollment estimates for K through 8 and high schools, as well as the number of motel rooms. The model
uses trip generation rates similar to those found in the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) Trip
In addition to providing projected peak hour and daily traffic volumes, model outputs include ratios of
projected traffic volume to available roadway capacity (V/C ratios) on each roadway segment and
information on vehicle-miles of travel by facility type (freeway, arterial streets, etc.). These informational
reports can be used to compare projected conditions under the current General Plan with the impacts of
Land use data was prepared and traffic forecasts completed by Hexagon Transportation Consultants for
the proposed land use amendment using the City of Morgan Hill’s TDF model. Future model forecasts
were developed for each of the Year 2030 General Plan study scenarios. These forecasts are considered
“raw” model volume forecasts, which on their own do not represent future volume conditions, but are
simply used to forecast growth and travel pattern changes expected in the future due to the proposed
land use and / or roadway changes. To obtain the final traffic volume forecasts, raw model volume
forecasts in conjunction with existing count data are used. Future traffic volume forecasts are developed
by adding to the existing traffic count data the projected growth between the base (year 2007) and the
project condition (year 2030) model volume forecasts. The traffic growth for each of the study
intersections was calculated by taking the difference between the Base Year forecasts and the project
conditions traffic forecasts for each of the intersections.

i.b: Analysis Methodologies and Level of Service Standards

page.text: Traffic conditions at the study intersections were evaluated using level of service (LOS). Level of Service
is a qualitative description of operating conditions ranging from LOS A, or free-flow conditions with little or
no delay, to LOS F, or jammed conditions with excessive delays. The analysis methods are described
Laurel/DeRose and Laurel/Honda General Plan Amendments Traffic Analysis
Signalized study intersections are subject to the City of Morgan Hill level of service standards. The City of
Morgan Hill level of service methodology is TRAFFIX, which is based on the 2000 Highway Capacity
Manual (HCM) method for signalized intersections. TRAFFIX evaluates signalized intersections
operations based on average delay time for all vehicles at the intersection. Since TRAFFIX is also the
CMP-designated intersections level of service methodology, the City of Morgan Hill methodology employs
the CMP defaults values for the analysis parameters, which include adjusted saturation flow rates to
reflect conditions in Santa Clara County. All intersections within the City of Morgan Hill are required to
meet the City’s LOS standard of LOS D, with the exception of the following:
LOS F for Downtown intersections and segments including at Main/Monterey, along Monterey
Road between Main and Fifth Street, and along Depot Street at First through Fifth Street;
LOS E for the following intersections and freeway zones:
Main Avenue and Del Monte Avenue
Dunne Avenue and Del Monte Avenue

As prescribed in the CMP technical guidelines, the level of service for freeway segments is estimated

The vehicle density on a segment is correlated to level of service as shown in Table 3. The CMP specifies

that are two lanes wide in one direction. A capacity of 1,650 vphpl was used for high occupancy vehicle
(HOV) lanes. The CMP defines an acceptable level of service for freeway segments as LOS E or better.

Station is located along Depot Street, with main access and parking off of Butterfield Boulevard,
approximately one mile from the project site. At the Morgan Hill Station, Caltrain provides service with
approximately 30- to 40-minute headways during commute hours.

Land use amendments for two sites are evaluated within this report: the Laurel-DeRose site and the
Laurel-Honda site. The project sites are located adjacent to one another, in the northwest quadrant of the
Dunne Avenue and US 101 interchange. The Laurel-DeRose site consists of a 6.81-acre vacant lot
located west of the 4.64-acre vacant Laurel-Honda site.
The proposed amendments consist of the change of the currently adopted General Plan land use for
each of the sites. Currently, there are no specific development plans for the project sites. However, for the
purposes of this study, maximum development scenarios on each of the project sites were evaluated,
based on information provided by City staff. The proposed land use amendments include the following:
At the Laurel-DeRose site (hereafter referred to as the Laurel-DeRose project), the currently adopted
General Plan land use designation and zoning for the site is Multi-Family Low on 4.54 acres and

Commercial on 2.27 acres. The proposed amendment includes the conversion of the Commercial portion
of the site to Multi-Family Low to include up to 95 dwelling units on the entire project site.
At the Laurel-Honda site (hereafter referred to as the Laurel-Honda project), the currently adopted
General Plan land use designation and zoning for the site is Multi-Family Low on 2.32 acres and
Commercial on 2.32 acres. The proposed amendment includes the conversion of the Multi-Family Low
portion of the site to Commercial that can include approximately 8,400 s.f. of commercial space and up to

The magnitude of traffic produced by a new development and the locations where that traffic would
appear are estimated using a three-step process: (1) trip generation, (2) trip distribution, and (3) trip
assignment. In determining project trip generation, the magnitude of traffic entering and exiting the site is
estimated for the AM and PM peak hours. As part of the project trip distribution step, an estimate is made
of the directions to and from which the project trips would travel. In the project trip assignment step, the
project trips are assigned to specific streets and intersections in the study area. These procedures are
described further in the following sections.
Through empirical research, data have been collected that correlate to common land uses their
propensity for producing traffic. Thus, for the most common land uses there are standard trip generation
rates that can be applied to help predict the future traffic increases that would result from a new
development. Hexagon has prepared project trip estimates for the proposed land use amendments based
on trip generation rates obtained from the Institute of Transportation Engineers’ (ITE’s) Trip Generation
Potential development on the Laurel-DeRose site consists of the development of up to 95 residential
condominium/townhouse. Based on the ITE trip generation rates, it is estimated that development on the
Laurel-DeRose site would generate 552 daily trips, with 42 trips (7 inbound and 35 outbound) occurring
during the AM peak hour and 49 trips (33 inbound and 16 outbound) occurring during the PM peak hour.
Potential development on the Laurel-Honda project site consists of the development of a 90-room hotel
and approximately 8,400 s.f. of commercial space, which could include a high-turnover restaurant and a
drive-thru fast food restaurant. Trip generation for retail/commercial uses is typically adjusted to account
for pass-by-trips. Pass-by-trips are trips that would already be on the adjacent roadways (and are
therefore already counted in the existing traffic) but would turn into the site while passing by. Justification
for applying the pass-by-trip reduction is founded on the observation that such retail traffic is not actually
generated by the retail development, but is already part of the ambient traffic levels. Pass-by-trips are
therefore excluded from the traffic projections (although pass-by traffic is accounted for at the site
entrances). A pass-by trip reduction of 20% was applied to the commercial component of the proposed
Laurel-Honda project during the PM peak hour, as recommended by ITE’s Trip Generation Handbook.
Based on the ITE trip generation rates and reductions for pass-by trips, it is estimated that the Laurel-
Honda site would generate 2,973 daily trips, with 252 trips (134 inbound and 118 outbound) occurring
during the AM peak hour and 180 trips (97 inbound and 83 outbound) occurring during the PM peak hour.

The results of the CMP freeway level of service analysis under existing plus project conditions for the
Laurel-DeRose site are summarized in Table 10. Traffic volumes on the study freeway segments under
existing plus project conditions were estimated by adding project trips associated with the potential
development on the Laurel-DeRose site to the existing volumes obtained from the 2012 CMP Annual
Monitoring Report. The results show that the Laurel-DeRose project would not cause an increase in traffic
volumes of one percent or more of freeway capacity on any freeway segment analyzed; nor would the
addition of project traffic result in the degradation of level of service on any freeway segment currently
operating at an acceptable LOS E to an unacceptable LOS F. Therefore, based on CMP impact criteria,
the potential development on the Laurel-DeRose site would not have a significant impact on freeways.
